  "prompt": "What is BHP of an engine?",
  "response": "BHP stands for \"Brake Horsepower,\" which is a measure of an engine's power output. Specifically:\n\n1. Definition:\n- It represents the power an engine produces before power losses from mechanical friction and other auxiliary components\n\n2. Calculation:\n- Measured using a dynamometer (brake) that applies load to the engine\n- Calculated at a specific RPM (revolutions per minute)\n\n3. Key points:\n- Indicates the engine's raw power potential\n- Different from wheel horsepower (WHP), which measures power actually reaching the wheels\n- Typically higher than the net horsepower rating\n\n4. Example:\n- If an engine is rated at 200 BHP, it means it can produce 200 horsepower at its peak performance point\n\n5. Usage:\n- Commonly used in automotive and engineering specifications\n- Helps compare engine performance across different vehicles or machinery\n\n6. Historical context:\n- Originally derived from comparing power to a horse's pulling capacity\n- Standardized measurement in mechanical engineering\n\nBHP provides a standard way to quantify and compare engine performance across different models and manufacturers.",
